The price of bitcoin first reached a maximum of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, five months later it fell to $2, today it is moving at the border of about ten dollars (a summary of the rates is shown on bitcoincharts.com).
Compared to the world’s exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which was released in October.
Bitcoin describes itself as “the most unsuccessful virtual money”, “competitive dollar and euro” and “a common money trick.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is like “credits” used to proceed in a video game that a person gets a game or can buy (and sometimes exchange it back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority monitors and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all network nodes are book depositors of ordinary accounts, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses by e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A file of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the transaction’s eligibility.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of ordinary accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to record this new transaction in this book.
It takes place by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, some temporary central banker, will be entitled to fill this additional line.
This is the cutting phase of a file; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then they "split up" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific print (e.g. zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check its accuracy.
The transaction will then indestructibly appear connected to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would have changed the print.
If the user wants to pay twice the same money for fraudulent purposes very quickly (up to ten minutes), the network will only confirm one of the two transactions - the second will be abandoned because each of them has a different footprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is divided regularly into two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided by up to a hundred million, so the space for margin here is...
The difficulty of a given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and there has been a robbery of stored bitcoins.
“The used coin does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also monitors the possibility of laundering dirty money thanks to this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Notable players such as Wikipedia reject the gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed a book of ordinary accounts and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, “huge discounts” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul dealing with the conversion of bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book about this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but uses the Bitcoin system to authenticate transactions that are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the carrier manages its identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easily set up for merchants where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, Pierre Noizat said, adding that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement of questioning of hierarchical systems and the transition to more horizontal systems.
“Before Bitcoin is implemented, it will take a while, but 2013 could be decisive,” he predicts.
Furthermore, in its report, the ECB envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
