Difficult work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Mursi has moved on to the next game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play a vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of all others, that the Constituent Assembly will approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this meeting another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been supplemented many times, weakening the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal agreements.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country’s fragmentation.
From the opposition point of view, the president continues in his "autocratic delirium", continues to "violate his word" and "weakens the law".
However, his supporters assure that it is a means of tackling the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerating the transition process.
There should be a referendum in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of explaining the text to the Egyptians article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country is rejecting protests.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Particularly because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: “Either approve my text, or I will have unlimited powers”, which should otherwise end after the adoption of the new constitution.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 members of the above-mentioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent in the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was announced, they knocked on the door with no opportunity to express their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their step.
In order to achieve resilience, 11 people from the ranks of substitutes were quickly supplemented yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further suspended the fact that one of the many disputes that day revolved around... hours of prayer, when some members of the committee argued that the hours in the meeting room were not properly arranged.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and states that "the principles of sharia law are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the key requirements, hoped to replace the term "basic" with the term "rules", which would allow stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their good will and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrites,” oppose the liberals, who see only the rhetorical problem in it.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts al-Azhar University with an advisory role, in particular on matters of checking compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "the people elected to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of theocracy.”
The fears of liberals are even more exasperating by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
“So far, there has been no specific religious repercussions.
By virtue of this constitution, Egypt remains a civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulamians, but university workers, many of whom have graduated in French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be contradictions as to the interpretation of Article 220, since the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, ozn. red.].
And in the future, the question may arise, to what extent civil judges are competent to express themselves.”
The text approved yesterday, in addition to the religious pages, is highly criticised for the extended powers granted to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant restriction on them compared to the former regime.
Another controversial place: the powers entrusted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military representatives, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, military courts will not prohibit the treatment of civilians, as demanded by the Association for the Protection of Human Rights.
These associations speak of their doubts in the context of the text, which they believe is directed against freedom.
The criminal act of harassment is preserved and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, protests are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
