Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the next few years participated in a number of projects of the Agency.
Of course, Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts devoted themselves to spaceflight before the Second World War; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, A. Sternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entering the Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his entry into space in France.
The mentioned doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous propagator of cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the opposite side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railroad trench was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should have been used to start the trench or to slow it down.
Information about this dredge is only known from the periodic press.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to circumnavigate with missiles.
The research was provided by the Weapons Technology Cell in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckieg.
From the preserved materials, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket was published in the professional press, designed by the engineer Rohozinski, and the following year the work of the Leliwy-Krzywoblock<0xC3><0xBD> air torpedo and aeronautical bomb was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of rocket engines.
Shortly before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (TIC) was responsible for all projects of military use of missile technology, which coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended the beginning of the war.
After the war, other papers on space science appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Tovarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time mention of the company is made in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problems, which contains four more extensive articles on astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society that will deal with cosmonauts.
Projects of artificial satellites were already under way at the time, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has sought to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and PTA has become a regular member already in the fall.
And the following year, the first president of the PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has contributed significantly to the development of the highly successful RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a reach of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959 two-stage RM-2 missile flight tests were launched in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of development was to be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have access to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor altitude winds.
However, in 1962, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM missiles was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and its starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (labelled Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in size of space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket was available space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aeronautical Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg up to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites under the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remk.
